<subSubSection id="C327657AEF3D4A5EABA38EEBFC27FCF4" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8236F1EF3D4A5EABA38EEBFEB5FD6D" blockId="93.[189,310,648,674]" box="[189,310,648,674]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
<heading id="D0CA819DEF3D4A5EABA38EEBFEB5FD6D" bold="true" box="[189,310,648,674]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B949EAE3EF3D4A5EABA38EEBFEB5FD6D" bold="true" box="[189,310,648,674]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8236F1EF3D4A5EABA38ED4FC27FCF4" blockId="93.[189,1399,695,827]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">This species has a distinctive scutellum, with the lateral band extremely broad so that the lateral scutellum is compressed into a narrow crenulated sulcus. This, along with the T1 being extremely sharply narrowing posteriorly from a broad anterior width, means this species is very unlikely to be conspecific with any of the newly described Australian species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
